hese models rest on assumptions about the nature of truth and existence that cannot be treated as exhaustive of modernist form.Lisi traces an alternative aesthetics of dependency that provides a different formal structure, philosophical foundation, and historical condition for modernist texts. Taking Europe's Scandinavian periphery as his point of departure, Lisi examines how Søren Kierkegaard and Henrik Ibsen imagined a response to the changing conditions of modernity different from those at the European core, one that subsequently influenced Henry James, Hugo von Hofmannsthal, Rainer Maria Rilke, and James Joyce.Combining close readings with a broader revision of the nature and genealogy of modernism, Marginal Modernity challenges what we understand by modernist aesthetics, their origins, and their implications for how we conceive of our relation to the modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aAesthetics in literature. 0aDependency (Psychology) in literature. 0aModernism (Literature). 0aPhilosophy in literature. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aAesthetics.  aHenrik Ibsen.  aHenry James.  aHugo von Hofmannsthal.  aJ.L. Heiberg.  aJames Joyce.  aModernism.  aPhilosophy and Literature.  aRainer Maria Rilke.  aSøren Kierkegaard.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311118960408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831107072980 cprintz978082324532140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823245352?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823245352423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823245352/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Pre